Exited Unicorn Companies¶

In [17]:
# Assuming you want to plot a count of each country in a column called 'Top Countries'
top_countries = exited_df_3['Country'].value_counts().nlargest(10).index

# Filter the dataframe to include only the top 10 countires
df_top_countries = exited_df_3[exited_df_3['Country'].isin(top_countries)]

# Create a bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.set(style="whitegrid")  # Set the style of the plot

ax = sns.countplot(data=df_top_countries, x='Country', color="darkseagreen", order=top_countries)

plt.title('Top 10 Countries Distribution of Exited Unicorn Companies', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Country', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')

plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')  # Rotate x-axis labels for better visibility

# Add counts to the bars
for p in ax.patches:
    ax.annotate(f'{p.get_height()}', (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()),
                ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10, color='black', fontweight='bold', xytext=(0, 5),
                textcoords='offset points')

plt.show()

The majority of unicorn companies in the United States have exited, as indicated by the above chart. China comes in second.

In [23]:
# Split the values in the column by commas and strip whitespaces
emerging_df_3['Lead Investors Include'] = emerging_df_3['Lead Investors Include'].str.split(',').apply(lambda x: [i.strip() for i in x])

# Create a new DataFrame to store the comma-separated data
df_split = pd.DataFrame(emerging_df_3['Lead Investors Include'].tolist(), index=emerging_df_3.index).stack().reset_index(level=1, drop=True).reset_index(name='split_values')

# Count the unique values in the column
unique_values_count = df_split['split_values'].value_counts()

# Assuming you want to plot a count of each investor in a column called 'Top Investors'
top_investors = df_split['split_values'].value_counts().nlargest(10).index

# Filter the dataframe to include only the top 10 investors
df_top_investors = df_split[df_split['split_values'].isin(top_investors)]

# Create a bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.set(style="whitegrid")  # Set the style of the plot

ax = sns.countplot(data=df_top_investors, x='split_values', color="lightsalmon", order=top_investors)

plt.title('Top 10 Investors Distribution of Emerging Unicorn Companies', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Investor', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')

plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')  # Rotate x-axis labels for better visibility

# Add counts to the bars
for p in ax.patches:
    ax.annotate(f'{p.get_height()}', (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()),
                ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10, color='black', fontweight='bold', xytext=(0, 5),
                textcoords='offset points')

plt.show()

According to the above bar chart, SoftBank Vision Fund invests in the majority of emerging unicorn companies. Tiger Global Management is the second largest investor in emerging unicorns.

Bivariate Analysis:¶

Exited Unicorn Companies¶

In [32]:
# Assuming you want to plot a count of each industry in a column called 'Top Industries'
top_industries = exited_df_3['Main Industry'].value_counts().nlargest(10).index

# Filter the dataframe to include only the top 10 industries
df_top_industries = exited_df_3[exited_df_3['Main Industry'].isin(top_industries)]

# Create a bar chart with hue='Main Reason'
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.set(style="whitegrid")  # Set the style of the plot

ax = sns.countplot(data=df_top_industries, x='Main Industry', hue='Main Reason', palette='turbo_r', order=top_industries)

plt.title('Main Exit Reasons for the Top 10 Industries', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Industry', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')

plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')  # Rotate x-axis labels for better visibility

# Remove counts from the bars
for p in ax.patches:
    ax.annotate('', (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()),
                ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10, color='black', fontweight='bold', xytext=(0, 5),
                textcoords='offset points')

plt.legend(title='Main Reason', title_fontsize='12', loc='upper right', bbox_to_anchor=(1.15, 1))

plt.show()

According to the above chart, bankruptcy is the reason for the company's exit in all of the top ten industries of the exited unicorn companies. The second most important reason for an IPO. Only unicorn companies in the software and technology industries, as well as the e-commerce and retail industries, have exited due to devaluation.

# Assuming you have the 'investor_counts' DataFrame
investor_counts_column = investor_counts['Investor_Count']

# Get the count of each unique value
count_of_each_unique_value = investor_counts_column.value_counts()

# Increase the size of the plot
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))

# Plotting the bar chart
bars = plt.bar(count_of_each_unique_value.index, count_of_each_unique_value.values, color='lightslategrey')

# Adding counts on top of the bars
for bar in bars:
    yval = bar.get_height()
    plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2, yval + 0.1, round(yval, 1), ha='center', va='bottom', fontweight='bold')

# Adding labels and title
plt.xlabel('Investor Count', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Number of Companies', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
plt.title('Distribution of Investor Counts in Existing Unicorn Companies', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')

# Adding labels to each tick on the x-axis
plt.xticks(count_of_each_unique_value.index, count_of_each_unique_value.index)

# Display the plot
plt.show()

Eventhough there are 1490 companies here the total count of companies is 1488, considering that there are two countries with identical names in the company list. It's important to note that these entries are not duplicates; rather, they represent two distinct companies with similar names. Despite the name similarity, they are separate entities.

# Assuming 'Emerging_Companies.csv' has columns 'Lead Investors Include' and 'Country'
existing_df_3 = pd.read_csv("Unicorn_Companies.csv", encoding='unicode_escape')

# Splitting the 'Lead Investors Include' column and creating new rows
investor_list = existing_df_3['Lead Investors Include'].str.split(', ')
investor_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Investor': investor_list.sum(),  # Flatten the list of lists
    'Country': existing_df_3['Country'].repeat(investor_list.apply(len))
})

# Counting the number of investors for each country
investor_counts = investor_df.groupby('Country').count().reset_index()
investor_counts.columns = ['Country', 'Investor_Count']

# Counting the number of companies for each country
company_counts = existing_df_3['Country'].value_counts().reset_index()
company_counts.columns = ['Country', 'Company_Count']

# Merging the two dataframes on the 'Country' column
result_df = pd.merge(investor_counts, company_counts, on='Country', how='outer').fillna(0)

# Display the result
print(result_df)

df = pd.DataFrame(result_df)

# Sorting by Investor_Count for better visualization
df = df.sort_values('Investor_Count', ascending=False)

# Selecting the top 10 countries
df_top10 = df.head(10)

# Plotting
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 8))

color = 'red'
ax1.set_xlabel('Country', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
ax1.set_ylabel('Investor Count', color=color, fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
ax1.plot(df_top10['Country'], df_top10['Investor_Count'], color=color, marker='o', label='Investor Count')
ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color)
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')

ax2 = ax1.twinx()  # instantiate a second axes that shares the same x-axis

color = 'blue'
ax2.set_ylabel('Company Count', color=color, fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')  # we already handled the x-label with ax1
ax2.bar(df_top10['Country'], df_top10['Company_Count'], color=color, alpha=0.5, label='Company Count')
ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color)

fig.tight_layout()  # otherwise the right y-label is slightly clipped
plt.title('Top 20 Investor and Company Count by Country', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.show()

The graph above demonstrates that as the number of companies in every country declines, so does the number of investors.
